post_text:
Say it with Signs Campaign
To help recognize the accomplishments of our students, Goffstown School District is looking to place small yard signs in high-visibility areas around our community. Please take a minute and let us know if you are willing to accommodate a sign if you live in a highly visible area. Signs will be installed between today and June 1st. They will be picked up between June 15th and July 1st. Goffstown School District will not be sharing any personal contact information with any outside groups.

If you have a space to offer for a sign, please complete this form: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1zcqQAGmphnZmAcbPO4Nj3lTfOdSI7oKqO-O-s5THs0g/edit?usp=sharing

To Parents/Guardians of Students Receiving Special Education Supports/Services:

The NH Department of Education periodically requires school districts to survey parents of students with special needs to determine their overall satisfaction with special education processes and services. We would love your input! We do receive feedback on our survey results and use this information to make improvements. Thank you in advance for your participation and thoughtful feedback.

You can access the survey by clicking the link below or copying and pasting it into a browser window.

bit.ly/nhdoefamilyk12

Our school is collecting non-perishable food items for the Goffstown Network. This local pantry gives to families in need and provides food to some of our students through the Weekend Food Program. Maple Avenue staff and students will be gathering food items from now until November 22nd.
Here are some of the suggested items: canned soup, canned beans, canned fruit, and canned vegetables, boxed rice and pasta, cereal bars, juice boxes and baking mixes. Please help us, help others in need.

The STEAM program at Maple Avenue Elementary School is underway! Exploration “Frog Metamorphosis” and “Helicopter Rescue” is in motion.

post_text:
Eastern Equine Encephalitis (EEE) has been detected in mosquitoes trapped in neighboring Manchester. Spraying to control mosquitoes will take place in Goffstown on Monday, October 14, 2019 from 4:00 PM to 8:30 PM at the following locations: Lions Field, Maple Avenue Elementary School, Bartlett Elementary School, Glen Lake Preschool, Goffstown High School and Mountain View Middle School

People may not be present during spraying. The locations above may be used the following morning.

The insecticide CrossCheck Plus (Bifenthrin 7.9%) will be used to control mosquitoes. Applications will be made using backpack sprayers. No road spraying is scheduled. Dragon Mosquito Control, Inc. of Brentwood will be the applicator. Residents may email help@dragonmosquito.com, call Dragon at 734-4144 or send a message on Facebook at Dragon Mosquito Control Inc. for information regarding dates, locations, insecticides and precautions.

Inquiring minds at work:
Knowing how to research a topic is taught at each grade level. Our classroom teachers plan and co-teach the research process with our media specialist.

Featured in the pictures below are third grade students from Mrs. Talbot’s class who are learning to use an online resource collection to research extreme weather hazards; as well as fourth grade students from Mrs. Mordecai’s class who are sorting through NH brochures to learn about historic landmarks in order to plan a 3-day NH “staycation”.

Maritime Signal Flags:
Many of our students are learning the language of signal flags. Ships use them to communicate with other ships. A series of flags can spell out a message, as each flag represents a letter. The TS Kennedy’s signal flags show its call sign, KVMU. Maple Avenue students used the signal flag alphabet to spell out their names.

The Maple Avenue community will be participating in a service-learning project from January 7 through February 22 to benefit the Liberty House Veterans Transitional House in Manchester, NH.
Liberty House assists over 200 local homeless and struggling Veterans. With the support of our Student Council, students will be collecting donations of peanut butter, boxes of Mac & Cheese, reusable bags, and new towels and donate these items to this organization.

To learn more about the Liberty House please visit their website: http://libertyhousenh.org.

Our 3rd and 4th grade Student Council held their first meeting this week. This group of 24 student leaders will help organize service learning projects and spirit days with our entire school population along with putting in volunteer hours inside and outside of school as a way to give back to their community.
Student Council Advisors Amy Goudreau, Christina Lamson, and Nicole Magoon volunteer their time to work with these enthusiastic students.

post_text:
Makerspace: Allowing students to think outside of the box, while using items contained in a bag.

Students in grades one through four visited the Library’s Makerspace this week. They received a mystery bag with a challenged inside. Using the materials provided, each student created an object that solved their challenge. They used creativity, imagination, and ingenuity to complete their task.

Full “STEAM” Ahead!

Students at Maple Ave Elementary School are taking part in STEAM challenges that build active inquiry, critical thinking skills, and cooperative challenges.

In these photos, students are working together to use everyday objects to design and engineer rafts that can float while supporting the weight of 20 pennies. Students were not only successful they also enjoyed the challenge!

The Department of Safety - Division of Fire Safety and the New Hampshire Fire Prevention Society believe that Fire Prevention and Life Safety should be a part of daily life all year long in every New Hampshire home. To help raise awareness, students are asked to design a poster that depicts an important fire prevention or safety theme. This contest is held annually and is open to all third grade students in the state of New Hampshire.

This year, Lajla F. from Mrs. Lamson’s 3rd grade classroom had her drawing selected to represent the month of May. She was presented with a plaque at an award ceremony on March 29th. Congratulations, Lajla!

post_text: These 1st graders compared New Hampshire’s climate with the St. Thomas Virgin Islands as part of their Follow The Voyage experience. They all decided that they would rather be on the island of St. Thomas this weekend with the Massachusetts Maritime Academy cadets, than be in chilly New Hampshire!

post_text: Many students at Maple Avenue School have been following the Sea Term voyage, of the Training Ship Kennedy! The cadets from the Massachusetts Maritime Academy have arrived at their first port of call in Cartagena, Colombia. A few of our 1st grade students are showing off their colorful depictions, of this country’s flag.

post_text: Last month, our student council helped the American Red Cross by collecting new stuffed animals. These stuffed animals will go to children who have been impacted by a disaster such as a house fire. The volunteers from the Red Cross picked up 235 stuffed animals from our school yesterday!
